{
  "text": "The role of endocytosis has been implicated in cellular responses to abiotic stress. Mitogen-activated protein kinase pathways have been shown to regulate the endocytic pathway under stress conditions in mammalian cells [CITATION_1] . Similarly, osmotic stress activates distinct mitogen-activated protein kinase pathways in plant cells [CITATION_2] ). The small GTPase Rab5 is one of the key regulators of early endocytic events in mammals. The plant homolog of Rab5 can be induced by salt stress and has been shown to function in the endocytic pathway in Arabidopsis [CITATION_3] Ueda et al., 2001) . Although detailed molecular mechanisms linking abiotic stress and endocytosis in plants are lacking, saline or osmotic stress does trigger the activation of endocytic uptake of a biotinylated endocytic marker in rice cells [CITATION_4] , and overexpression of At-Rab7 increases salt and osmotic stress tolerance, which is consistent with accelerated membrane endocytosis [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, genetic studies have demonstrated the importance of endocytosis for plant fitness under stress [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . These observations have led to the hypothesis that plants have developed a more efficient internalization mechanism to retrieve membrane materials to help them adapt to abiotic stress. CSCs may represent The CSCs are believed to be assembled in the Golgi apparatus and then secreted to the PM through the TGN/EE. It is largely unknown how secretory vesicles (SV) containing CSCs fuse to the PM, an exocytosis process that may involve actin. Microtubules are involved in docking the secretory vesicle, as SmaCCs/ MASCs were often observed to be associated with microtubules. CSI1 mediates the CSC-microtubule interaction. CSCs are internalized through AP2/CME. Newly endocytosed vesicles containing CSCs are predicted to be recycled to the PM through SmaCC-mediated fast recycling and TGN/EE-mediated slow recycling. a type of cargo that utilizes this efficient internalization mechanism under abiotic stress.",
  "correct_citation": {
